A077001.name: a(1) = 1, a(n+1) is the largest squarefree number <= n*a(n).

A077002.name: a(1) = 1, a(n+1) is the largest triangular number <= n*a(n).

A077003.name: a(n)= index of triangular number A077002(n).

A077005.name: Smallest k such that prime(n) divides k*prime(n-1) + 1, n > 1.

A077006.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n)/n >= sigma(m)/m for all m <= n.

A077007.name: Primes (k) such that prime(k)*prime(k+1) + 1 or prime(k)*prime(k+1)- 1 is divisible by prime(k+2).

A077008.name: Legendre symbol (-1,p) where p is the n-th prime.

A077011.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains all possible products of n-1 of the first n primes in ascending order.

A077012.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains all possible products of n-1 of the first n natural numbers in ascending order.

A077013.name: Number of different argument values of vector sums generated by n vectors chosen from 2n (equally spaced) points around the unit circle. Arguments are considered different only up to rotation and reflection.

A077014.name: Number of ways that a directed line (or river) that starts in the south can cross an east-west road n times.
formula: Equals A005316(n) if n odd, or 2*A005316(n) if n even (because then each solution to A005316 can be reflected in a vertical mirror to give another solution).

A077015.name: a(1) = 1, continue by multiplying by the smallest composite number and then dividing by the smallest prime not used earlier and taking the integer part at every step.

A077016.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 4, continue by dividing by the smallest prime not used earlier and multiplying with the smallest composite number just greater than the previous prime used in the division and then take the integer part at every step.

A077017.name: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) = smallest positive integer divisible by the n-th prime that also has a nontrivial common divisor with a(n).

A077018.name: Closest prime to n (break ties by taking the larger prime).

A077019.name: a(n) is the smallest number for which the prime distance A051699 is equal to n.

A077020.name: a(n) is the unique odd positive solution x of 2^n = 7x^2+y^2.
formula: a(n) = 2^(n-2) * a(4-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 05 2017
0 = 8*a(n)^2 + 2*a(n+1)^2 - a(n+2)^2 - a(n+3)^2 for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 05 2017
2*a(n) + a(n+1) = a(n+2) or a(n+3). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 05 2017

A077021.name: a(n) is the unique odd positive solution y of 2^n = 7x^2 + y^2.
formula: a(n+2) = abs(A002249(n)). - _Artur Jasinski_, Oct 05 2008 [With correction by _Jianing Song_, Nov 21 2018]

A077022.name: Values of n such that sum of first n primes squared is divisible by n-th prime.

A077023.name: Integer values of sum of first n primes squared divided by n-th prime, for some n (A077022).

A077026.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} floor(n/k + 1)-floor(n/k + 1/2).
formula: Conjecture: Let f(a,b)=1, if (a+b) mod |a-b| != (a mod |a-b|)+(b mod |a-b|), and 0 otherwise. a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} 1-f(n,k). - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Sep 22 2016

A077027.name: Number of simple integral graphs on n nodes.
formula: Euler transform of A064731. - _Eric M. Schmidt_, Mar 23 2015

A077028.name: The rascal triangle, read by rows: T(n,k) (n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n) = k(n-k) + 1.
formula: As a square array read by antidiagonals, a(n, k) = 1 + n*k. a(n, k) = a(n-1, k) + k. Row n has g.f. (1+(n-1)x)/(1-x)^2, n >= 0. - _Paul Barry_, Feb 22 2003

Still thinking of square arrays. Let f:N->Z and g:N->Z be given and I an integer, then define a(n, k) = I + f(n)*g(k). Then a(n, k)*a(n-1, k-1) = a(n-1, k)*a(n, k-1) + I*(f(n) - f(n-1))*(g(k) - g(k-1)) for suitable n and k. S= (E*W + 1)/N. arises with I = 1, and f = g = id. - _Terry Lindgren_, Apr 10 2011

Using the above: Having just read J. Fleron's nice article in Discovering the Art of Mathematics on the rascal triangle, it is neat to note and straightforward to show that when I = 1, a(n, k) + a(n-1, k-1) = a(n-1, k) + a(n, k-1) + (f(n) - f(n-1))*(g(k) - g(k-1)), so with I = 1, and f = g = id, we have S+N = E+W + 1, as his students discovered. - _Terry Lindgren_, Nov 28 2016
T(n, k) = A128139(n-1, k-1). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 02 2012

T(n, k) = 0 if n < k, T(n, 0) = 1, T(n,n) = 1, for n >= 0, and T(n, k) = (T(n-1, k-1)*T(n-1, k) + 1)/(T(n-2, k-1)) for 0 < k < n. See the first comment referring to the triangle with its apex in the middle. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Dec 19 2017

A077029.name: Rectangle R(i,j) by antidiagonals; column j has j-1 zeros followed by numbers congruent to 1 mod j-1.

A077034.name: a(1)=3; a(2n), a(2n+1) are smallest integers > a(2n-1) such that a(2n-1)^2+a(2n)^2=a(2n+1)^2.

A077035.name: a(1)=7; a(n),a(n+1) are smallest > a(n-1) such that a(n-1)^2+a(n)^2=a(n+1)^2.

A077037.name: Largest prime < n^3.
formula: a(n) > (n-1)^3 for all large n, by Ingham's theorem (see A060199). - _Jonathan Sondow_, Mar 27 2014

A077038.name: Least difference of primes p, q such that p < n^3 < q.

A077039.name: Sums of first n signatured primes (A073579).
formula: a(n) = -Sum_{k=2..n} A000040(k)*i^(A000040(k)+1) where i is the imaginary unit. - _Anthony Browne_, May 17 2016

A077040.name: Primes p such that abs(A077039(A049084(p))) <= p.

A077041.name: Primes p such that abs(A077039(A049084(p))) > p.

A077042.name: Square array read by falling antidiagonals of central polynomial coefficients: largest coefficient in expansion of (1 + x + x^2 + ... + x^(n-1))^k = ((1-x^n)/(1-x))^k, i.e., the coefficient of x^floor(k*(n-1)/2) and of x^ceiling(k*(n-1)/2); also number of compositions of floor(k*(n+1)/2) into exactly k positive integers each no more than n.
formula: By the central limit theorem, T(n,k) is roughly n^(k-1)*sqrt(6/(Pi*k)).
T(n,k) = Sum{j=0,h/n} (-1)^j*binomial(k,j)*binomial(k-1+h-n*j,k-1) with h=floor(k*(n-1)/2), k>0. - _Michel Marcus_, Dec 01 2012

A077043.name: "Three-quarter squares": a(n) = n^2 - A002620(n).
formula: Also can be computed from 1 * C(n,0) + 2 * C(n,1) + 2 * C(n,2) - Sum((-2)^(k-3) C(n, k)). - _Joshua Zucker_, Nov 10 2002
a(n+1) - a(n) = A001651(n), partial sums of A001651. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Dec 28 2007
The inverse binomial transform yields 0 followed by A141531. (End)
Euler transform of length 3 sequence [3, 1, -1]. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 29 2011
Sum_{k=0..n} a(2k+1) = partial sums of A003215 = (n+1)^3 (see example). - _Philippe Deléham_, Dec 17 2011
a(n) = Sum_{j=1..n} Sum_{i=1..n} ceiling((i+j-n)/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 12 2015
a(n) = (3*n)^2/12 for n even and a(n) = ((3*n)^2 + 3)/12 for n odd. - _Miquel Cerda_, Jun 30 2016
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} floor((n+k)/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 31 2017
0 = 1 +a(n)*(+a(n+1) -a(n+2)) +a(n+1)*(-3 -a(n+1) +a(n+2)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 02 2017

A077044.name: Largest coefficient in expansion of (1 + x + x^2 + ... + x^(n-1))^5 = ((1-x^n)/(1-x))^5, i.e., the coefficient of x^floor(5*(n-1)/2) and of x^ceiling(5*(n-1)/2); also number of compositions of floor(5*(n+1)/2) into exactly 5 positive integers each no more than n.

A077045.name: Doubly restricted composition numbers: number of compositions of 1+2+3+...+n = n(n+1)/2 into exactly n positive integers each no more than n.
formula: a(n) = A077042(n, n). Roughly n^(n-3/2)*sqrt(6/Pi) by the central limit theorem and something like n^n*sqrt(6/(Pi*(n^3+0.3*n^2-0.91*n+0.3)) seems to be even closer.
a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..floor((n-1)/2)} binomial(n,k)*binomial(n + binomial(n,2) - n*k - 1, n-1)*(-1)^k for n >=1. - _Emanuele Munarini_, Jul 15 2016

A077046.name: Doubly restricted composition numbers: number of compositions of [n^2/2] into exactly n positive integers each strictly less than n.

A077047.name: Doubly restricted composition numbers: number of compositions of floor(n(n+2)/2) into exactly n positive integers each no more than n+1.
formula: a(n) ~ exp(1) * sqrt(6/Pi) * n^(n-3/2). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 26 2016

A077048.name: Doubly restricted composition numbers: number of compositions of [n^2/2] into up to n positive integers each no more than n.

A077049.name: Left summatory matrix, T, by antidiagonals upwards.
formula: T(n,k)=1 if k|n, otherwise T(n,k)=0, k >= 1, n >= 1.
As linear sequence a(n) = floor(A004736(n)/A002260(n)) - floor((A004736(n)-1)/A002260(n)); a(n) = floor(j/i)-floor((j-1)/i), where i=n-t*(t+1)/2, j=(t*t+3*t+4)/2-n, t=floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). (End)

A077050.name: Left Moebius transformation matrix, M, by antidiagonals.
formula: M = T^(-1), where T is the left summatory matrix, A077049.

A077051.name: Right summatory matrix, T, by antidiagonals.
formula: T(n, k)=1 if n|k else T(n, k)=0.
As linear sequence a(n) = floor(A002260(n)/A004736(n)) - floor((A002260(n)-1)/A004736(n));
a(n) = floor(i/j) - floor((i-1)/j), where i=n-t*(t+1)/2, j=(t*t+3*t+4)/2-n, t=floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). (End)
G.f. for row n: x^n/(1-x^n). - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Mar 29 2015

A077052.name: Right Moebius transformation matrix, M, by antidiagonals.
formula: M=T^(-1), where T is the right summatory matrix, A077051.

A077053.name: Greatest common divisor of indecomposable Wallis pairs.

A077054.name: Number of ways a river can cross a road 2n times.

formula: For n odd a(n) = (A005316(n)+2*A223096(floor(n/2)))/4. [_Stéphane Legendre_, Apr 09 2013]

A077056.name: Total number of "humps" in all A005316(2n) open meanders with 2n crossings.

A077057.name: Minimal positive solution a(n) of Diophantine equation a(n)^2 - a(n)*b(n) - G(n)*b(n)^2 = +1 or -1 with G(n) := A078358(n). The companion sequence is b(n)=A077058(n).

A077058.name: Minimal positive solution a(n) of Diophantine equation b(n)^2 - b(n)*a(n) - G(n)*a(n)^2 = +1 or -1 with G(n) := A078358(n). The companion sequence is b(n)=A077057(n).

A077059.name: Numbers j such that j^2 + k^2 is a cube for some k > j.
formula: j is in this sequence if for some integer k > j, j^2 + k^2 = c^3.

A077060.name: Smallest k>A077059(n) such that A077059(n)^2+k^2 is a cube (=A077061(n)^3).

A077062.name: Minimal k > n such that n^2 + k^2 is a cube for k > n, or 0 if no such k exists.

A077070.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the power of 2 in denominator of coefficients of Legendre polynomials, where n >= 0 and 0 <= k <= n.

A077071.name: Row sums of A077070.
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to 2*n^2 and it seems that a(n) = 2*n^2 + O(n^(3/2)) (where O(n^(3/2))/n^(3/2) is bounded and O(n^(3/2)) < 0). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 30 2002
G.f.: 1/(1-x)^2 * sum(k>=0, t/(1-t), t=x^2^k). Twice the value of the partial sum of A005187. a(0) = 0, a(2n) = a(n)+a(n-1)+4n^2+2n, a(2n+1)=2a(n)+4n^2+6n+2. - _Ralf Stephan_, Sep 12 2003

A077072.name: Nonzero transfer matrix elements for strip of width n.

A077073.name: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) is smallest prime factor of (2 * Product_{k=1..n} a(k)) + 1.

A077074.name: Least k such that Z(k,3) <= Z(n,4) where Z(m,s) = Sum_{i>=m} 1/i^s.

A077075.name: Least k such that Z(k,4) <= Z(n,5) where Z(m,s) = Sum_{i>=m} 1/i^s.

A077078.name: Number of different absolute values of vector sums generated by n vectors chosen from 2n (equally spaced) points around the unit circle. Dipole moments of n positive and n negative equally spaced charges on a circle.

A077079.name: Number of inequivalent bracelets from A006840 with the additional equivalence condition that subsets of 1-beads whose position vectors add to zero can be removed. Different values of vector sums of (-1)^(k/n) with k taking n values in 1..2n up to rotation and reflection.

A077081.name: Fixed point when phi(sigma(n)+phi(n))=A077080 is iterated with initial value of n.

A077084.name: Fixed points in order of appearance when Phi[Sigma[n]+phi(n)]=A077080 is iterated with increasing initial values(n); A077083[a(n)]=1.

A077086.name: Remainder when sigma(n+1) is divided by sigma(n).

A077087.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n+1) = 3 * sigma(n).

A077088.name: a(n) = phi(sigma(n) - phi(n)), where phi is Euler's totient function and sigma is the sum of divisors function, with a(1) = 0.

A077096.name: Starting iteration of Phi[]*(Sigma[]-Phi[]) function at these initial values leads to the fixed point 8064.

A077097.name: Quotient cycle length in continued fraction expansion of sqrt(1+n^n).

A077098.name: Length of period of the continued fraction expansion of sqrt(-1+n^n).

A077099.name: a(n) = gcd(A051612(n), A065387(n)), where A051612(n) = sigma(n) - phi(n) and A065387(n) = sigma(n) + phi(n).

A077100.name: a(n) = lcm(A051612(n), A065387(n)), where A051612(n) = sigma(n) - phi(n) and A065387(n) = sigma(n) + phi(n).
formula: If p is prime, then a(p) = 2*p.

A077101.name: a(n) = A051612(n)*A065387(n) = sigma(n)^2-phi(n)^2, where A051612(n) = sigma(n) - phi(n) and A065387(n) = sigma(n) + phi(n).

A077102.name: Smallest m such that GCD[a+b,a-b]=n, where a=sigma[n],b=phi[n].

A077103.name: Numbers n such that gcd(a,b) is not equal to gcd(a+b,a-b), where a=sigma(n)=A000203(n) and b=phi(n)=A000010(n).
formula: gcd(A000010(n), A000203(n)) is not equal to gcd(A065387(n), A051612(n)); or A055008(n) is not equal to A077099(n).

A077105.name: Number of nonisomorphic generalized Petersen P(n,k) graphs on 2n nodes for 1<=k<=floor((n-1)/2).

A077114.name: Least k such that Z(k,5) <= Z(n,6) where Z(m,s) = Sum_{i>=m} 1/i^s.

A077116.name: n^3 - A065733(n).
formula: a(n) = A154333(n) unless n is a square or, equivalently, a(n)=0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 05 2013

A077117.name: Least k such that Z(k,6) <= Z(n,7) where Z(m,s) = Sum_{i>=m} 1/i^s.

A077120.name: n^3 times nearest integer square to n^3.

A077122.name: Let M_n be the n X n matrix M_(i,j) = 2^i-2^j then the characteristic polynomial of M_n = x^n-a(n)*x^(n-2).

A077123.name: Let M_n be the n X n matrix M_(i,j) = i!-j! then the characteristic polynomial of M_n = x^n+a(n)*x^(n-2).

A077124.name: Decimal expansion of the constant c such that A003096(n-1) = ceiling(c^(2^n)).

A077125.name: Decimal expansion of the constant c such that A007018(n)=floor(c^(2^n)).
formula: c = E^2 where E is the Vardi constant arising in the Sylvester sequence (A076393). - _Gerald McGarvey_, Dec 08 2007

A077127.name: a(0) = 1, a(1) = 2, a(n) = smallest number other than n, non-coprime to n and not occurring earlier.

A077128.name: Smallest number greater than the previous term which is relatively prime to each of the group of the next n numbers.

A077129.name: Smallest number which is relatively prime to all the numbers between successive odd primes.

A077130.name: Smallest number which is relatively prime to all the numbers between n^2 and (n+1)^2, inclusive.

A077133.name: Difference between the sum of odd-indexed primes and even-indexed primes.

A077135.name: Composite numbers n whose proper (other than 1 and n) odd divisors are prime and even divisors are 1 less than a prime.

A077136.name: Composite numbers n whose proper divisors (excluding 1 and n) are all of the form p or p+1, with p prime.

A077138.name: a(0) = 0. If n is odd, a(n) = a(n-1) + n, otherwise a(n) = a(n-1) * n.

A077140.name: a(1) = 1 and then add n to the previous term if n is coprime to the previous term, otherwise subtract n from the previous term. a(1) = 1 and a(n) = a(n-1) + n if gcd(n, a(n-1)) = 1, otherwise a(n) = a(n-1) - n.
formula: a(1) = 1 and a(n) = a(n-1) + n if gcd(n, a(n-1)) = 1, otherwise a(n) = a(n-1) - n.
Abs(a(n)) = ((n+1) mod 2)*n + (floor((n+(n mod 2))/2) mod 2). - Tj Wrenn (tjwrenn(AT)cs.utexas.edu), Apr 07 2005

A077141.name: Decimal expansion of the constant c such that A000289(n) = ceiling(c^(2^n)) + 1.

A077143.name: Floor[ product of next n primes /sum of next n primes].

A077144.name: Floor[ product of next n composite numbers / sum of next n composite numbers].

A077145.name: Floor[ product of next n primes / product of next n composite numbers].

A077146.name: Floor[ concatenation of next (n+1) numbers / concatenation of next n numbers].

A077148.name: Smallest k such that there are n numbers m relatively prime to n in range n < m < k.

A077149.name: a(1) =3. For n>1, a(n) = smallest k such that there are n numbers m not relatively prime to n in range n < m < k.

A077150.name: Number of composite numbers between n and 2n that are coprime to n.
formula: a(n) = phi(n) + Pi(n) - Pi(2n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 18 2011

A077151.name: Index of the first occurrence of n in A077150, or 0 if n does not occur.

A077152.name: Smallest k such that there are n primes between n and k.

A077153.name: Smallest k such that there are n composite numbers greater than n and smaller than k.

A077154.name: Smallest k such that there are as many composite numbers less than n as there are between n and k.

A077161.name: Final terms of rows of triangle in A077159.

formula: a(n) = n^A002024(n) = n^round(sqrt(2*n)). - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Nov 01 2002

A077164.name: Triangle in which n-th row gives n numbers relatively prime to n and greater than all earlier terms in the triangle.
formula: a(n) = A071977(n) for n>1. - _Georg Fischer_, Oct 06 2018

A077165.name: Leading terms of rows in A077164.

A077166.name: Final terms of rows in A077164.

A077170.name: Final terms of rows of A077168.

A077173.name: Initial terms of rows of triangle in A077172.

A077174.name: Final terms of rows of triangle in A077172.

A077175.name: Product of terms in n-th row of triangle in A077172.

A077181.name: Smallest number k such that k*prime(n) is a concatenation of successive integers starting from 1.

A077193.name: Number of multiples of n that can be obtained by permuting the digits of number formed by the concatenation of first n numbers.

A077194.name: Smallest multiple of n with least digit sum.

A077196.name: Smallest possible sum of the digits of a multiple of n.
formula: a(2n)=a(n) and a(5n)=a(n) for any n. In particular, a(2^a*5^b) = a(1) = 1 where a or b are nonnegative integer.

A077197.name: a(n) = lambda(phi(n)) where lambda(n) (A002322) is the Carmichael lambda function which gives the smallest integer m such that k^m = 1 mod n for all integers k relatively prime to n and phi(n) is A000010.

A077198.name: a(n) = lambda(sigma(n)), where lambda(n) is the Carmichael lambda function, which gives the smallest integer m such that k^m = 1 mod n for all integers k relatively prime to n.

A077199.name: Smallest k such that both k and k+n are squarefree.

A077202.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest number such that the concatenation of two successive terms gives a prime which has not occurred earlier.

A077203.name: a(1) = 2. Then the smallest n-digit prime starting with the last digit of the previous term.

A077204.name: a(1) = 1 . Then smallest n-digit square (MSD) starting with the LSD of the previous term and not a multiple of 100.

A077206.name: a(1) = 1 and then smallest n-digit triangular number starting with the least significant digit of the previous term and not a multiple of 10.

A077208.name: Rearrangement of squarefree numbers such that a(k) begins with the end of a(k-1).

A077209.name: a(1) = 2, then the smallest squarefree number greater than the previous term that begins with the end of the previous term.

A077210.name: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) is the smallest squarefree number greater than n*a(n).

A077211.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) is the smallest square greater than n*a(n).

A077213.name: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) is the smallest prime greater than n*a(n).

A077214.name: a(1) = 1. a(n+1) is the smallest number which is greater than a(n), coprime to it and has a different prime signature.

A077215.name: Prime power with largest index that divides the product of composite numbers between successive primes with a(1) = a(2) = 1.

A077216.name: Smallest prime(k) such that 2^n divides the product of composite numbers between prime(k) and prime(k+1) but 2^(n+1) does not.

A077217.name: Prime(k) such that the prime power with largest exponent that divides the product P(k) of composite numbers between prime(k) and prime(k+1) is an odd number, i.e., if p^r and 2^s divide P(k) then r >= s, p is an odd prime.

A077218.name: Sum of numbers of prime factors (counted with multiplicities) of numbers between n-th and (n+1)-st prime.

A077219.name: Floor(geometric mean of the reduced residue system modulo n).

A077220.name: a(1) = 1; thereafter a(n) is smallest number not occurring earlier such that a(n-1)+a(n) is a triangular number.

A077221.name: a(0) = 0 and then alternately even and odd numbers in increasing order such that the sum of any two successive terms is a square.
formula: a(n) = 2*n^2 + 4*n + 1 [+1 if n is odd] with a(0)=1.
Row sums of triangle A131925; binomial transform of (1, 7, 2, 4, -8, 16, -32, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 29 2007
a(n) = a(-n); a(n+1) = A195605(n) - (-1)^n. - _Bruno Berselli_, Sep 22 2011

A077222.name: a(1) = 1 and then alternately the smallest even and odd numbers not occurring earlier such that the sum of two successive terms is a square.

A077223.name: a(1) = 1 and then alternately even and odd numbers not occurring earlier such that the sum of two successive terms is a squarefree number.

A077224.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = smallest number > a(n-1) such that a(n) + a(k) is squarefree for k = 1 to n-1.
formula: It can easily be proved that a(n) == 1 mod 4 for all n >3.

A077225.name: Starting with a(0)=1, smallest squarefree number k such that, for all a(m), m<n, k+a(m) is not squarefree.

A077226.name: Inverse of A051261, i.e., (n, a(n), a(n)) is a winning position in 3-pile Wythoff game.

A077227.name: Triangle of compositions of n into exactly k parts each no more than k.
formula: G.f. of column k is: x^k*(1-x^k)^k/(1-x)^k for k>=1. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 25 2013

A077228.name: Triangle of compositions with a total that is no more than n into exactly k parts each no more than k.

A077229.name: Number of compositions of n where the largest part is less than or equal to the number of parts.
formula: G.f.: 1 + sum(n>=1, q^n * ( (1-q^n)/(1-q) )^n ), the g.f. above, slightly rewritten. [_Joerg Arndt_, Mar 30 2014]

A077230.name: Numerators of coefficients of series expansion of a certain integral in the theory of charged particle beams.
formula: a(n) = numerator(sum(k=1..n, 4^(-k)*binomial(2*k,k)*sum(j=1..k, (j!*binomial(k,j)*(-1)^(j)*stirling1(n+j,j))/(n+j)!))), n>0, a(0)=2. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 18 2015

A077231.name: Denominators of coefficients of series expansion of a certain integral in the theory of charged particle beams.

A077232.name: a(n) is smallest natural number satisfying Pell equation a^2 - d(n)*b^2= +1 or = -1, with d(n)=A000037(n) (a nonsquare). Corresponding smallest b(n)=A077233(n).

A077233.name: a(n) is smallest natural number satisfying Pell equation b^2- d(n)*a^2= +1 or = -1, with d(n)=A000037(n) (nonsquare). Corresponding smallest b(n)=A077232(n).

A077234.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = 2*S(n, 4)+S(n-1, 4), with S(n, x) = U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind, A049310. S(-1, x) = 0 and S(n, 4) = A001353(n+1).
a(n) = 4*a(n-1)-a(n-2) with a(0)=2 and a(1)=9. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 16 2008

A077235.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = 2*T(n+1, 2)+T(n, 2), with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 2)= A001075(n).
a(n) = 4*a(n-1)-a(n-2) with a(0)=5 and a(1)=16. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 16 2008

A077236.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - a(n-2) with a(0) = 4 and a(1) = 11.
formula: a(n) = T(n+1,2) + 2*T(n,2), with T(n,x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n,2) = A001075(n).

A077237.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A054491 and A077234.

A077238.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A077236 and A077235.

A077239.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = 2*T(n+1, 3)+T(n, 3), with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 3)= A001541(n).

A077240.name: Bisection (even part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = T(n+1, 3)+2*T(n, 3), with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 3)= A001541(n).

A077241.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A054488 and A077413.

A077242.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A077240 and A077239.

A077243.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n)= 2*S(n, 8)+S(n-1, 8), with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind, A049310. S(n, 8)= A001090(n+1).

A077244.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n)= (2*T(n+1, 4)+T(n, 4))/3, with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 4)= A001091(n).

A077245.name: Bisection (even part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n)= S(n, 8)+2*S(n-1, 8), with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev's polynomials of the 2nd kind, A049310. S(-1, x) := 0 and S(n, 8)= A001090(n+1).

A077246.name: Bisection (even part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n)= (T(n+1, 4)+2*T(n, 4))/3, with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 4)= A001091(n).

A077247.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A077245 and A077243.

A077248.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A077246 and A077244.

A077249.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = 2*S(n, 10)+S(n-1, 10), with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind, A049310. S(n, 10)= A004189(n+1).

A077250.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = 2*T(n+1, 5)+T(n, 5), with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 5)= A001079(n).

A077251.name: Bisection (even part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 10)+2*S(n-1, 10), with S(n, x) = U(n, x/2), Chebyshev's polynomials of the 2nd kind, A049310. S(n, 10)= A004189(n+1).

A077252.name: Sum of digits squared minus sum of digits of n.

A077253.name: Sum of digits squared plus sum of digits of n.

A077255.name: Numbers n such that prime(n)^n == 1 (mod n).

A077256.name: Primes p such that p^k == 1 modulo k, where p=prime(k).

A077257.name: Differences between two successive prime powers of prime numbers (A076707) in more than one way.

A077258.name: Least number which can be represented by the difference between two successive prime powers of prime numbers (A076707) in just n ways.

A077259.name: First member of the Diophantine pair (m,k) that satisfies 5*(m^2 + m) = k^2 + k; a(n) = m.
formula: a(n) = (A000045(A007310(n+1))-1)/2. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 02 2002 [corrected by _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 16 2009]
a(n) = a(-1-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 15 2018
a(2*n) = A049651(2*n); a(2*n+1) = A110679(2*n+1). See "6 interlaced bisections" link. - _Hermann Stamm-Wilbrandt_, Apr 18 2019

A077260.name: Triangular numbers that are 1/5 of a triangular number.
formula: a(n) = (A000045(A007310(n+1))^2-1)/8. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 02 2002. - Definition corrected by _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 16 2009

A077261.name: Triangular numbers that are 5 times another triangular number.

A077262.name: Second member of the Diophantine pair (m,k) that satisfies 5*(m^2 + m) = k^2 + k; a(n) = k.
formula: a(n) = (-1 + sqrt(8*b(n) + 1))/2 where b(n) are the entries in A077261.
a(n) = (sqrt(5*A000045(A007310(n+1))^2 - 4) - 1)/2. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 02 2002. - Definition corrected by _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 16 2009
a(n) = 18*a(n-2) - a(n-4) + 8. - _Vladimir Pletser_, Mar 23 2020 ; a(-2) = -6, a(-1) = -1, a(0) = 0, a(1) = 5. [Edited by _Vladimir Pletser_, Jul 26 2020]
Can be defined for negative n by setting a(-n) = - a(n-1) - 1 for all n in Z.

A077263.name: Number of (undirected) cycles in the n-th order antiprism graph.

A077264.name: Table of arithmetic sequences, by antidiagonals.

A077265.name: Number of cycles in the n-th order prism graph.
formula: a(n) = A000079(n) + A002378(n-1). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, May 07 2014

A077266.name: Triangle of number of zeros when n is written in base k (2 <= k <= n).
formula: T(nk, k)=T(n, k)+1; T(nk+m, k)=T(n, k) if 0<m<k; T(k, k)=1; T(n, k)=0 if n/2<k<n or 0<n<k.

A077267.name: Number of zeros in base-3 expansion of n.
formula: a(n) + A062756(n) + A081603(n) = A081604(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 23 2003
a(n) = A079978(n) if n < 3, A079978(n) + a(floor(n/3)) otherwise. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 21 2013

A077268.name: Number of bases in which n requires at least one zero to be written.

A077269.name: Number of connected squarefree graphs on n nodes.
formula: Inverse Euler transform of A006786. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 03 2017

A077273.name: Ordered differences without repetitions between two successive powers of a prime but not a prime (A025475).

A077274.name: Differences between two successive powers of a prime but not a prime (A025475) in more than one way.

A077275.name: Least number which can be represented by the difference between two successive powers of a prime but not a prime (A077273) in just n ways.

A077279.name: Last prime of n-th group of successive primes in A073684.

A077280.name: Sum of next a(n) successive primes is a square.

A077281.name: Square root of sum of successive primes in n-th group in A077280.

A077282.name: First prime in n-th group in A077280.

A077283.name: Last prime in n-th group in A077280.

A077285.name: Number of partitions of n with designated summands.
formula: Expansion of eta(q^6) / (eta(q) * eta(q^2) * eta(q^3)) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 05 2004
Euler transform of period 6 sequence [ 1, 2, 2, 2, 1, 2, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 05 2004
G.f.: P(x)*P(x^2)*P(x^3)/P(x^6), where P(x)=Product_{k>0} 1/(1-x^k) is the partition generating function (A000041).
a(n) = Sum_{k>=1} k*A266477(n,k). - _Alois P. Heinz_, Dec 29 2015
G.f.: Product_{i>0} (1 + Sum_{j>0} j*x^(j*i)). - _Seiichi Manyama_, Oct 08 2017

A077286.name: Primes which are not the difference between two successive perfect powers (A001597).

A077288.name: First member of the Diophantine pair (m,k) that satisfies 6(m^2 + m) = k^2 + k: a(n) = m.
formula: a(n) = a(-1-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 15 2018

A077289.name: Triangular numbers that are 1/6 of another triangular number.
formula: Let b(n) be A077288. Then a(n)=b(n)*(b(n)+1)/2.

A077290.name: Triangular numbers that are 6 times other triangular numbers.

A077291.name: Second member of Diophantine pair (m,k) that satisfies 6*(m^2 + m) = k^2 + k: a(n) = k.
formula: Let b(n) be A077290. Then a(n) = (-1 + sqrt(8*b(n) + 1))/2.
Can be defined for negative n by setting a(-n) = - a(n-1) - 1 for all n in Z.

A077292.name: Numbers k with the property that k divides one of the concatenations (k-1)(k-2) or (k-2)(k-1).

A077293.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings nontrivially (a(n) is not equal to n) such that the n-th string is a multiple of n.

A077295.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are even, all different and > 2. (0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077296.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 3) all different and > 3. ( 0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077297.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 4, all different and > 4. ( 0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077298.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 5, all different and > 5. ( 0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077299.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 6, all different and > 6. ( 0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077300.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 7, all different and > 7 ( 0 is never taken as the most significant digit).

A077301.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 8, all different and > 8. ( 0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077302.name: Partition the concatenation 1234567...of natural numbers into successive strings which are multiples of 9, all different and > 9. ( 0's never taken as the most significant digit.)

A077303.name: Partition the concatenation 235711131719232931...of prime numbers into successive strings such that the n-th string is a multiple of n and >n..

A077304.name: Partition the concatenation 235711131719232931...of prime numbers into successive strings such that the n-th string is a multiple of prime(n) and > prime(n).

A077305.name: Partition the concatenation 468910121415161820212224252627283032... of composite numbers into successive strings such that the n-th string is a multiple of prime(n) and > prime(n).

A077306.name: Smallest multiple of n formed by the concatenation of n successive numbers, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077307.name: Partial sums of theta series of diamond (A005925).

A077309.name: Concatenation of n numbers starting with n.

A077310.name: Smallest multiple of n that is a concatenation of (increasing) natural numbers starting with(n+1).

A077312.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation of natural numbers from (n+1) to k is a multiple of n.

A077316.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the k-th prime = 1 (mod n).

A077317.name: a(n) is the n-th prime == 1 (mod n).

A077318.name: Sum of terms in n-th row of A077316.

A077319.name: Average of terms in n-th row of A077316.

A077320.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains n smallest multiples of the n-th prime.
formula: T(n,k) = k*prime(n) with 1 <= k <= n. - _Bruno Berselli_, Sep 05 2017

A077321.name: Rearrange primes so as to form a triangle in which n-th row contains the n smallest primes == 1 (mod n) which have not occurred earlier.

A077322.name: Initial terms of rows of A077321.

A077323.name: Final terms of rows of A077321.

A077324.name: Sum of terms of n-th row of A077321.

A077325.name: Average of terms of n-th row of A077321.

A077326.name: Smallest number beginning with 1 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077327.name: Smallest number beginning with 2 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077328.name: Smallest number beginning with 3 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077329.name: Smallest number beginning with 4 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077330.name: Smallest number beginning with 5 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077331.name: Smallest number beginning with 6 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077332.name: Smallest number beginning with 7 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077333.name: Smallest number beginning with 8 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077334.name: Smallest number beginning with 9 and having exactly n distinct prime divisors.

A077335.name: Sum of products of squares of parts in all partitions of n.
formula: Recurrence: a(n) = (1/n)*Sum_{k=1..n} b(k)*a(n-k), where b(k) = Sum_{d divides k} d^(2*k/d + 1).
a(n) = S(n,1), where S(n,m) = n^2 + Sum_{k=m..n/2} k^2*S(n-k,k), S(n,n) = n^2, S(n,m) = 0 for m > n. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Sep 07 2014
G.f.: exp(Sum_{k>=1} Sum_{j>=1} j^(2*k)*x^(j*k)/k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 14 2018

A077336.name: Smallest squarefree number beginning with n.

A077337.name: Numbers n such that n and R(n) both are squarefree where R(n) (A004086) is the digit reversal of n.

A077338.name: a(n) = smallest multiple of prime(n) such that a(n) +1 is a multiple of prime(n+1).

A077339.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains the first n numbers beginning with n.

A077340.name: Final terms of rows in A077339.

A077341.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains the first n numbers, not already present, that begin with n.

A077343.name: Final terms of rows in A077341.

A077344.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains n smallest primes beginning with n.

A077345.name: a(n) is the n-th prime whose decimal expansion begins with the decimal expansion of n.

A077346.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains n smallest squares beginning with n.

A077347.name: Final terms of rows of A077346.

A077350.name: Smallest number beginning with n and having exactly n divisors.

A077351.name: Smallest multiple of n using all the digits of all its divisors (a permutation of the concatenation of its divisors), or 0 if no such number exists.

A077352.name: a(n) = (concatenation in ascending order of divisors of 2^n)/2^n.

A077353.name: a(n) = (concatenation in ascending order of divisors of 5^n)/5^n.

A077354.name: a(n) = Sum_{i=n+1..2n} prime(i) - Sum_{i=1..n} prime(i).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} (prime(n+i) - prime(i)), where prime(i) = A000040(i).

A077355.name: Squares whose internal digits form a square.

A077356.name: Squares whose external digits (MSD and LSD) form a square. Or squares from which deleting the internal digits leaves a square.

A077357.name: Squares whose external digits (MSD and LSD) as well as internal digits form squares.

A077359.name: Primes whose external digits form a prime. Or primes from which deleting the internal digits leaves a prime.

A077360.name: Primes whose external digits as well as internal digits form a prime.

A077361.name: Smallest n-digit prime whose external digits as well as internal digits form a prime, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077362.name: Largest n-digit prime whose external digits as well as internal digits form a prime, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077363.name: Smallest n-digit square whose external digits as well as internal digits form a square, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077364.name: Largest n-digit square whose external digits as well as internal digits form a square, or 0 if no such number exists.

formula: Recurrence: a(n) = 1/n*Sum_{k=1..n} b(k)*a(n-k), where b(k) = Sum_{d divides k} d*d!^(k/d).

A077366.name: Triangular numbers whose internal digits form a triangular number. Or triangular number such that deleting the MSD and LSD leaves a triangular number.

A077367.name: Triangular numbers whose external digits form a triangular number. Or triangular number whose MSD and LSD form a triangular number.

A077373.name: Fibonacci numbers whose external digits as well as internal digits form a Fibonacci number.

A077375.name: Numbers k such that 2^k + prime(k) is prime.

A077376.name: Squarefree numbers whose internal digits form a squarefree number.

A077377.name: Squarefree numbers whose external digits form a squarefree number.

A077378.name: Squarefree numbers whose external as well as internal digits form a squarefree number.

A077379.name: Smallest n-digit squarefree number whose internal as well as external digits form a squarefree number greater than 1; or 0 if no such number exists.

A077380.name: Largest n-digit squarefree number whose internal as well as external digits form a squarefree number, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077381.name: Number of squarefree numbers between successive squares (exclusive).
formula: a(n) > n for all n (Mincu and Panaitopol, 2006).

A077382.name: a(1) = 1, then multiply, add and subtract 2, 3, 4; 5, 6, 7; ... in that order.

A077383.name: a(1) = 1, then add, multiply and subtract 2, 3, 4; 5, 6, 7; ... in that order.

A077384.name: a(1) = 1, then add, multiply, subtract, multiply 2, 3, 4, 5; 6, 7, 8, 9; ... in that order.

A077386.name: Sums of rows of triangle in A077385.

A077387.name: Continued fraction expansion of Product_{p prime} (1 + p/((p-1)^2*(p+1))).

A077388.name: Sums of rows of triangle in A077389.

A077389.name: Smallest integer that is the average of n consecutive primes.

A077391.name: Smallest n-digit prime which leaves a prime at every step if most significant digit and least significant digit are deleted until a one digit or two digit prime is obtained, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A077393.name: Number of n-node simple graphs having clique number 6.

A077394.name: Number of n-node simple graphs having clique number 7.

A077395.name: Lesser of two successive squarefree numbers whose product is not squarefree.
formula: Conjecture: lim_{n->oo} n/a(n) > 0. - _Thomas Ordowski_ and _Robert Israel_, Aug 18 2015

A077396.name: Square roots of squares arising in A076991.

A077397.name: Expansion of (1+31*x-2*x^2-2*x^3)/(1-16*x^2+x^4).
formula: a(n) = 16*a(n-2) - a(n-4) for n>3. - _Colin Barker_, Jul 27 2020

A077398.name: First member of the Diophantine pair (m,k) that satisfies 7*(m^2+m) = k^2+k; a(n)=m.
formula: a(n) = 16*a(n-2) - a(n-4) + 7, n >= 3. [corrected by _Vladimir Pletser_, Feb 29 2020]
Let b(n) be A077397 then a(n+2) = 2*a(n+1) - a(n) + b(n) with a(0)=0 a(1)=2.

A077399.name: Triangular numbers that are 1/7 of triangular numbers.
formula: Let b(n) be A077398(n) then a(n) = b(n)*(b(n)+1)/2.

A077400.name: Triangular numbers that are 7 times triangular numbers.

A077401.name: Second member of Diophantine pair (m,k) that satisfies 7*(m^2 + m) = k^2 + k; a(n) = k.
formula: a(n) = 16*a(n-2) - a(n-4) + 7, n >= 2 with a(-2)=-7, a(-1)=-1, a(0)=0, a(1)=6. [Corrected by _Vladimir Pletser_, Feb 29 2020, Jul 26 2020]
Let b(n) be A077400(n); then a(n) = (-1 + sqrt(8*b(n) + 1))/2.
Can be defined for negative n by setting a(-n) = - a(n-1) - 1 for all n in Z.

A077402.name: Reverse and Add! carried out in base 3; number of steps needed to reach a palindrome, or -1 if no palindrome is ever reached.

A077403.name: In base 3: smallest number that requires n Reverse and Add! steps to reach a palindrome.

A077404.name: Trajectory of n under the Reverse and Add! operation carried out in base 3 (presumably) does not reach a palindrome.

A077405.name: Trajectory of n under the Reverse and Add! operation carried out in base 3 (presumably) does not reach a palindrome and (presumably) does not join the trajectory of any term m < n.

A077406.name: In base 3: n sets a new record for the number of Reverse and Add! steps needed to reach a palindrome starting with n.

A077407.name: In base 3, records for the number of Reverse and Add! steps needed to reach a palindrome.

A077408.name: Trajectory of 103 under the Reverse and Add! operation carried out in base 3, written in base 10.

A077409.name: Bisection (even part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = T(n+1, 5)+2*T(n, 5), with T(n, x) Chebyshev's polynomials of the first kind, A053120. T(n, 5) = A001079(n).

A077410.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A077249 and A077251.

A077411.name: Combined Diophantine Chebyshev sequences A077409 and A077250.

A077412.name: Chebyshev U(n,x) polynomial evaluated at x=8.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 16) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind. See A049310.

A077413.name: Bisection (odd part) of Chebyshev sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = 2*S(n, 6)+S(n-1, 6), with S(n, x) = U(n, x/2), Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind, A049310. S(n, 6) = A001109(n+1).

A077414.name: a(n) = n*(n - 1)*(n + 2)/2.
formula: a(n) = t(n,t(n,1)) + n, where t(n,k) = n*(n+1)/2 + k*n and t(n,1) = A000096(n). - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 28 2017
a(n) = n^3/2 + n^2/2 - n. - _Tanner Robeson_, Aug 23 2020

A077415.name: a(n) = n*(n+2)*(n-2)/3.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..floor((n-1)/2)} (-1)^i * 2^(n-2*i-1) * binomial(n-i-1, i) * (n-2*i-2). - _John M. Campbell_, Jan 08 2016

A077416.name: Chebyshev S-sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 12) + S(n-1, 12) = S(2*n, sqrt(14)) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind. See A049310. S(-1, x)=0, S(n, 12) = A004191(n).
a(n) = (ap^(2*n+1) - am^(2*n+1))/(ap - am) with ap := (sqrt(7)+sqrt(5))/sqrt(2) and am := (sqrt(7)-sqrt(5))/sqrt(2).

A077417.name: Chebyshev T-sequence with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 12) - S(n-1, 12) = T(2*n+1, sqrt(14)/2)/(sqrt(14)/2) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), resp. T(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second, resp. first, kind. See A049310 and A053120. S(-1, x)=0, S(n, 12)=A004191(n).
a(n) = (ap^(2*n+1) + am^(2*n+1))/sqrt(14) with ap := (sqrt(7)+sqrt(5))/sqrt(2) and am := (sqrt(7)-sqrt(5))/sqrt(2).

A077419.name: Largest Whitney number of Fibonacci lattices J(Z_n).
formula: a(n) ~ phi^(n+2) / (5^(1/4) * sqrt(2*Pi*n)), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 22 2017

A077420.name: Bisection of Chebyshev sequence T(n,3) (odd part) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = T(2*n+1, 3)/3 = S(n, 34) - S(n-1, 34), with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), resp. T(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second, resp. first, kind. See A049310 and A053120. S(-1, x)=0, S(n, 34)= A029547(n), T(n, 3)=A001541(n).

A077421.name: Chebyshev sequence U(n,11)=S(n,22) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 22) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the 2nd kind. See A049310.
a(n) = (ap^(n+1) - am^(n+1))/(ap - am) with ap := 11+2*sqrt(30) and am := 11-2*sqrt(30).

A077422.name: Chebyshev sequence T(n,11) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n+1)^2 - 30*(2*b(n))^2 = 1, n>=0, with the companion sequence b(n)=A077421(n).
a(n) = T(n, 11) = (S(n, 22)-S(n-2, 22))/2 = S(n, 22)-11*S(n-1, 22) with T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp. second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(n, 22)=A077421(n).
a(n) =  (ap^n + am^n)/2 with ap := 11+2*sqrt(30) and am := 11-2*sqrt(30).

A077423.name: Chebyshev sequence U(n,12)=S(n,24) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 24) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the 2nd kind. See A049310.
a(n) = (ap^(n+1) - am^(n+1))/(ap - am) with ap= 12+sqrt(143) and am = 12-sqrt(143).

A077424.name: Chebyshev sequence T(n,12) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n+1)^2 - 143*b(n)^2 = 1 for n>=0, with the companion sequence b(n)=A077423(n).
a(n) = T(n, 12)= (S(n, 24)-S(n-2, 24))/2 = S(n, 24)-11*S(n-1, 24) with T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp. second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(n, 24)=A077423(n).
a(n) = (ap^n + am^n)/2, with ap := 12+sqrt(143) and am := 12-sqrt(143).

A077425.name: a(n) == 1 (mod 4) (see A016813), but not a square (i.e., not in A000290).

A077426.name: Nonsquare integers n such that the continued fraction (sqrt(n)+1)/2 has odd period length.

A077427.name: Primitive period length of (regular) continued fraction of (sqrt(D(n))+1)/2 for D(n)=A077425(n).

A077428.name: Minimal (positive) solution a(n) of Pell equation a(n)^2 - D(n)*b(n)^2 = +4 with D(n)= A077425(n). The companion sequence is b(n)=A078355(n).

A077431.name: n repeated in decimal representation, but separated by enough zeros that the square has the pattern (n^2)(2n^2)(n^2).

A077432.name: Squares of the form u'v'w, where in decimal representation u=n^2, v=2*n^2 and w=n^2 possibly with a leading zero.

A077433.name: Number of separating zeros to represent A077431.

A077435.name: Number of right triangles whose vertices are lattice points in {1,2,...,n} X {1,2,...,n}.

A077436.name: Let B(n) be the sum of binary digits of n. This sequence contains n such that B(n) = B(n^2).

A077437.name: Squares whose decimal digits are nonsquares (2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 8).

A077438.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d|k} mu(d) mu(n/d)^2 = -1.

A077439.name: Numbers n such that n and n^2 have square decimal digits.

A077440.name: Squares and their roots having square decimal digits.

A077441.name: In base 4, smallest number that requires n Reverse and Add! steps to reach a palindrome.

A077442.name: 2*a(n)^2 + 7 is a square.
formula: The same recurrences hold for the odd and even indices respectively : a(n+2) = 6*a(n+1) - a(n), a(n+1) = 3*a(n) + 2*(2*a(n)^2+7)^0.5. - _Richard Choulet_, Oct 11 2007

A077443.name: Numbers k such that (k^2 - 7)/2 is a square.
formula: The same recurrences hold for the odd and the even indices: a(n+2) = 6*a(n) - a(n-2), a(n+1) = 3*a(n) + 2*(2*a(n)^2-14)^0.5 - _Richard Choulet_, Oct 11 2007
a(n) = A000129(n+1) -(-1)^n*A000129(n-2), rephrasing the formula above. - _Paul Curtz_, Dec 07 2012

A077444.name: Numbers k such that (k^2 + 4)/2 is a square.

A077445.name: Numbers k such that (k^2 - 8)/2 is a square.
formula: With a=3+2*sqrt(2), b=3-2*sqrt(2): a(n) = sqrt(2)*(a^((2*n-1)/2) + b^((2*n-1)/2)). a(n) = sqrt(2*A003499(2*n-1)+4). - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Mar 24 2003
a(n) = (2 + sqrt(2))*(3 + 2*sqrt(2))^n + (2 - sqrt(2))*(3- 2*sqrt(2))^n. - _Antonio Alberto Olivares_, Feb 23 2006
G.f.: 2*Q(0)*x*(1-x)/(1-3*x), where Q(k) = 1 + 1/( 1 - x*(8*k-9)/( x*(8*k-1) - 3/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 10 2013

A077446.name: Numbers n such that 2*n^2 + 14 is a square.
formula: Bisection: a(2*k+1) = S(k, 6) + 5*S(k-1, 6), a(2*k) = 5*S(n-1, 6) + S(n-2, 6), with the Chebyshev polynomials S(n, x) (A049310) with S(-2, x) = -1, S(-1, x) = 0, evaluated at x = 6. S(n, 6) = A001109(n-1). See A054490 and A255236, and the given g.f.s. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Feb 26 2015

A077447.name: Numbers n such that (n^2 - 14)/2 is a square.

A077448.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d|k} mu(d)*mu(k/d)^2 = +1.

A077449.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d|k} mu(phi(d)) = 0.
formula: a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n where c is around 5.47...

A077454.name: a(n) = sigma_3(n^3)/sigma(n^3).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(6*e+2) + p^(3*e+1) + 1)/(p^2 + p + 1). - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 09 2020

A077455.name: a(n) = sigma_4(n^4)/sigma(n^4).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(12*e+3) + p^(8*e+2) + p^(4*e+1) + 1)/(p^3 + p^2 + p + 1). - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 09 2020

A077456.name: a(n) = sigma_5(n^5)/sigma(n^5).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(20*e+4) + p^(15*e+3) + p^(10*e+2) + p^(5*e+1) + 1)/(p^4 + p^3 + p^2 + p + 1). - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 09 2020

A077459.name: Numbers k such that k and 3*k have the same digital binary sum.

A077460.name: Number of nonisomorphic ways a loop can cross a road (running East-West) 2n times.

A077463.name: Number of primes p such that n < p < 2n-2.

A077464.name: Stolarsky-Harborth constant; lim inf_{n->infty} F(n)/n^theta, where F(n) is the number of odd binomial coefficients in the first n rows and theta=log(3)/log(2).
formula: Equals lim inf_{n->oo} A006046(n)/n^A020857. - _Amiram Eldar_, Dec 03 2020

A077465.name: Values of n such that A006046(n)/n^theta, where theta=log(3)/log(2), is a local minimum, computed according to Harborth's recurrence.

A077467.name: Sum of binary digits of A077465(n).

A077468.name: Greedy powers of (2/3): sum_{n=1..inf} (2/3)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(2/3) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
It appears that, for n>1, a(n)=A073536(n-1) - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 04 2004

A077469.name: Greedy powers of (3/4): sum_{n=1..inf} (3/4)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(3/4) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 8.0... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077470.name: Greedy powers of (3/5): sum_{n=1..inf} (3/5)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(3/5) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 3.7... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077471.name: Greedy powers of (4/7): sum_{n=1..inf} (4/7)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(4/7) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 3.3... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077472.name: Greedy powers of (5/8): sum_{n=1..inf} (5/8)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(5/8) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 3.4... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077473.name: Greedy powers of (5/9): sum_{n=1..inf} (5/9)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(5/9) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 2.8... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077474.name: Greedy powers of (7/10): sum_{n=1..inf} (7/10)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(7/10) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 6... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077475.name: Greedy powers of (8/13): Sum_{n>=1} (8/13)^a(n) = 1.
formula: a(n)=sum_{k=1..n}floor(g_k) where g_1=1, g_{n+1}=log_x(x^frac(g_n) - x) (n>0) at x=(8/13) and frac(y) = y - floor(y).
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n with c around 3.7... - _Benoit Cloitre_

A077476.name: Numbers n such that the digital binary sum of n equals core(n), the squarefree part of n.

A077477.name: Least positive integers not excluded by the rule that if n is present then 2n+1 and 3n+1 are not allowed.

A077478.name: Rectangular array R read by antidiagonals: R(i,j) is the number of integers k that divide both i and j (i >= 1, j >= 1).
formula: R=U*V, where U and V are the summatory matrices (A077049, A077051). The triangle T(n, k) formed by antidiagonals: T(n, k)=tau(gcd(k, n+1-k)) for 1<=k<=n, where tau(m)=A000005(m). [Corrected by _Leroy Quet_, Apr 08 2009]
Dirichlet g.f.: Sum_{n>=1} Sum_{k>=1} tau(gcd(n,k))/n^s/k^c = zeta(s)*zeta(c)* zeta(s + c). - _Mats Granvik_, May 19 2021

A077479.name: Number of distinct prime factors of numbers m with BigOmega(m) == 0 modulo omega(m).

A077480.name: Total number of prime factors of numbers m with bigomega(m) == 0 modulo omega(m) (counted with repetition).

A077482.name: Number of self-avoiding walks on square lattice trapped after n steps.

A077483.name: Probability P(n) of the occurrence of a 2D self-trapping walk of length n: Numerator.

A077484.name: Probability P(n) of the occurrence of a 2D self-trapping walk of length n: Exponent of 2 in the denominator.

A077485.name: a(1) = 1, then smallest n-digit square which leaves a square at every step if most significant digit and least significant digit are deleted until a one-or two-digit digit square is obtained. a(2n) = 0 if no such square exists. a(2n+1) = 10^2n only if no nontrivial candidate exists.
formula: Beginning with term a(6) the following pattern applies: a(4k)=0; a(4k+1)=10^4k=(10^2k)^2; a(4k+2)=0; a(4k+3)=(10^(2k+1)+2)^2. - _Ray Chandler_, Aug 03 2003

A077486.name: Largest n-digit square which leaves a square at every step if most significant digit and least significant digit are deleted until a one- or two-digit square is obtained. a(2n) = 0 if no such square exists. a(2n+1) = 9*10^2n only if no nontrivial candidate exists.
formula: Beginning with term a(6) the following pattern applies: a(4k)=0; a(4k+1)=9*10^4k=(3*10^2k)^2; a(4k+2)=0; a(4k+3)=(2*10^(2k+1)+1)^2. - _Ray Chandler_, Aug 03 2003

A077487.name: Squares which leave a square at every step if most significant digit and least significant digit are deleted until a one-digit or two-digit square is obtained.

A077488.name: All possible products in increasing order of two distinct members of the unary sequence 1, 11, 111, 1111, 11111, ...given by A000042.

A077489.name: a(n) = smallest multiple of 4 with sum of digits = n.

A077490.name: a(n) = smallest k such that 4k has a digit sum = n.

A077491.name: a(n) = smallest k such that 2k has digit sum = n.

A077492.name: a(n) = smallest k such that 5k has a digit sum = n.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 10*a(n-9) - 10*a(n-10) for n > 14. - _Georg Fischer_, Oct 26, 2020

A077493.name: a(n) = smallest multiple of 7 with a digit sum = n.

A077494.name: a(n) = smallest k such that the digit sum of 7k is n.

A077495.name: a(n) = smallest k such that the digit sum of 8k is n.

A077496.name: Decimal expansion of lim n -> infinity A001699(n)^(1/2^n).

A077500.name: Primes of the form 2^r*p^s + 1, where p is an odd prime.

A077501.name: a(n) = smallest prime greater than a(n-1) and beginning with n.

A077502.name: Smallest square greater than the previous term and beginning with n.

A077503.name: Smallest n-digit square beginning with n.
formula: a(n) = ceiling(sqrt(n*10^d))^2 where d = n - digit(n), digit(n) = number of digits in n. - _Ray Chandler_, Aug 11 2003

A077504.name: Smallest n-digit prime beginning with n.

A077505.name: a(n) = A077504(n) - n*10^d where d = n - number of digits in n.

A077506.name: Smallest n-digit triangular number beginning with n.

A077507.name: Largest n-digit triangular number beginning with n.

A077508.name: Largest n-digit prime beginning with n.

A077509.name: a(n) = (n+1)*10^d - A077508(n) where d = n - number of digits in n.

A077510.name: Numbers n such that n + pi(n) is a prime.

A077511.name: Continued fraction expansion of lim n -> infinity A001699(n)^(1/2^n).

A077512.name: Largest n-digit square beginning with n.

A077513.name: Smallest n-digit squarefree number beginning with n.

A077514.name: Largest n-digit squarefree number beginning with n.

A077515.name: Smallest n-digit number beginning with n and having n divisors, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077516.name: Largest n-digit number beginning with n and having n divisors, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077517.name: a(1) = 1 and a(n+1) = smallest multiple of a(n) beginning in (n+1).

A077520.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest prime of the form k*a(n-1)+1 starting with n.

A077521.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest squarefree number which begins with n and is a multiple of the previous term.

A077522.name: Smallest number beginning with n and having exactly n prime divisors, all distinct.

A077525.name: Last term of n-th row of A077526.

A077526.name: Triangle in which the n-th row contains n palindromes beginning with n.

A077527.name: Row sums of triangle in A077526.

A077529.name: Triangle in which the n-th row contains n palindromic multiples of n, or 0's if no such palindromes exist.

A077530.name: Final terms of rows of A077529.

A077532.name: Average of terms in n-th row of A077529.

A077533.name: Multiples of 3 using only prime digits (2, 3, 5 and 7).

A077534.name: Multiples of 4 using only prime digits (2, 3, 5 and 7).

A077535.name: Multiples of 6 with only prime digits (2, 3, 5 and 7).

A077536.name: Multiples of 7 using only prime digits (2, 3, 5 and 7).

A077537.name: Sum of next F(n) Fibonacci numbers, where F(n) = n-th Fibonacci number.
formula: First differences of A005370 = F(F(n+1)+1). - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Nov 17 2002

A077538.name: First differences of triangular numbers with square pyramidal indices.
formula: Let SP(m) be the m-th square pyramidal number m*(m+1)*(2*m+1)/6 and let T(k) be the k-th Triangular number k*(k+1)/2; then a(n) = T(SP(n+1))-T(SP(n)) = ((n+1)^2*(n+2)*(2*n^2+2*n+3))/6.

A077539.name: a(n) = Floor[ T(n+1)!*T(n-1)!/{(T(n)!)^2}], where T(n) = n(n+1)/2 = the n-th triangular number.

A077540.name: a(n) = smallest multiple of the product of next n natural numbers which is a product of consecutive numbers starting with (k+1) where k = n(n+1)/2 = the n-th triangular number.

A077541.name: a(n) = A077540(n)/Pr(n), where Pr(n)= product of next n numbers. E.g. Pr(3) = 4*5*6.

A077542.name: Least number of terms required in the product (k+1)(k+2)... to make it a multiple of the product of next n number, where k = n(n+1)/2.
formula: Let A077540(n) = (k+1)(k+2)...(k+r) where k = n(n+1)/2 then a(n) = r.

A077544.name: Product of next n numbers + sum of next n numbers.

A077549.name: Rearrangement of primes so that the most significant decimal digit follows the cyclic pattern 1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9...

A077588.name: Maximum number of regions into which the plane is divided by n triangles.
formula: Proof (from _Joshua Zucker_ and _N. J. A. Sloane_, Dec 01 2017)

Represent the configuration of n triangles by a planar graph with a node for each vertex of the triangles and for each intersection point. Let there be v_n nodes and e_n edges. By classical graph theory, a(n) = e_n - v_n + 2. When we go from n to n+1 triangles, each side of the new triangle can meet each side of the existing triangles at most twice, so Dv_n := v_{n+1}-v_n <= 6n.
Each of these intersection points increases the number of edges in the graph by 2, so De_n := e_{n+1}-e_n = 3 + 2*Dv_n, Da_n := a(n+1)-a(n) = 3 + Dv_n <= 3+6*n.

These upper bounds can be achieved by taking 3n points equally spaced around a circle and drawing n concentric overlapping equilateral triangles in the obvious way, and we achieve a(n) = 3n^2 - 3n + 2 (and v_n = 3n^2, e_n = 3n(2n-1)) for n>0. QED

Indeed beginning with a(3) the terms contain exactly two 1 digits and the rest 0's up to this point. The term following 10^406+10 will introduce a third nonzero digit, perhaps a 1, but the pattern of the sequence changes dramatically at this point. - _Ray Chandler_, Aug 02 2003
