A077751.name: Smallest cube that begins and ends in n, or 0 if no such cube exists.

A077752.name: Smallest number whose cube begins and ends in n, or 0 if no such number exists.

A077754.name: Smallest multiple of n with two or more digits, none of them zeros, whose digit sum equals n, or 0 if no such multiple exists.

A077755.name: Array in which the n-th row contains the multiples of n using nonzero digits and having a digit sum of n. Sequence contains the rows and a zero entry for rows with no terms (e.g. 10).

A077757.name: Smallest n-digit multiple of n with digit sum n.

A077758.name: Largest n-digit multiple of n with digit sum n.

A077759.name: Smaller of the two successive triangular numbers which differ in the use of only one digit.

A077760.name: Nonsquares which in at least two ways are the product of two numbers with the same digits (leading zeros are forbidden).

A077761.name: Decimal expansion of Mertens' constant, which is the limit of (Sum_{i=1..k} 1/prime(i)) - log(log(prime(k))) as k goes to infinity, where prime(i) is the i-th prime number.
formula: Equals A001620 - Sum_{n>=2} zeta_prime(n)/n where the zeta prime sequence is A085548, A085541, A085964, A085965, A085966 etc. [Sebah and Gourdon] - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 29 2006

A077762.name: Number of ways of pairing the squares of the numbers 1 to n with the squares of the numbers n+1 to 2n such that each pair sums to a prime. Because an odd square must always be added to an even square to obtain a prime, this sequence is the product of A077763 and A077764.
formula: a(n) = permanent(m), where the n X n matrix m is defined by m(i,j) = 1 or 0, depending on whether i^2 + (j+n)^2 is prime or composite, respectively. - _T. D. Noe_, Feb 10 2007

A077763.name: Number of ways of pairing the odd squares of the numbers 1 to n with the even squares of the numbers n+1 to 2n such that each pair sums to a prime.

A077764.name: Number of ways of pairing the even squares of the numbers 1 to n with the odd squares of the numbers n+1 to 2n such that each pair sums to a prime. a(1) is defined to be 1.

A077765.name: Number of maximum-size antichains in partition lattice Par(n).

A077766.name: Number of primes of form 4k+1 between n^2 and (n+1)^2.

A077767.name: Number of primes of form 4k+3 between n^2 and (n+1)^2.

A077768.name: Number of times that the sum of two squares is an integer between n^2 and (n+1)^2; multiple representations are counted multiply.

A077769.name: Number of times that the sum of two coprime squares of opposite parity is an integer between n^2 and (n+1)^2; multiple representations are counted multiply.

A077770.name: Number of ordered pairs of integers (x,y) with n^2 < x^2 + y^2 < (n+1)^2; number of lattice points between circles of radii n and n+1.

A077771.name: Decimal value of the ternary Champernowne constant.

A077772.name: Continued fraction expansion of the ternary Champernowne constant.

A077773.name: Number of integers between n^2 and (n+1)^2 that are the sum of two squares; multiple representations are counted once.

A077774.name: Number of integers between n^2 and (n+1)^2 that are the sum of two coprime squares of opposite parity; multiple representations are counted once.

A077775.name: Odd numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/3 - 2*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime) of the form 3...313...3.

A077776.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1) - 8*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077777.name: Numbers k such that 7*(10^k - 1)/9 - 5*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077778.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1) - 7*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077779.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/9 + 2*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077780.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/9 + 3*10^floor(k/2) is palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077781.name: Numbers k such that 7*(10^k - 1)/9 - 3*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (also known as near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077782.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1) - 5*10^floor(m/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077783.name: Numbers k such that (10^k-1)/9 + 4*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077784.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/3 + 2*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077785.name: Odd numbers k such that the palindromic wing number (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindrome) 7*(10^k - 1)/9 - 2*10^((k-1)/2) is prime.

A077786.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1) - 4*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077787.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/9 + 5*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077788.name: Numbers k such that 7*(10^k - 1)/9 - 10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077789.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/9 + 6*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077790.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/3 + 4*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077791.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/9 + 7*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077792.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/3 + 5*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077793.name: Numbers k such that 7*(10^k - 1)/9 + 10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077794.name: Odd integers n such that 10^n - 1 - 10^((n-1)/2) is a prime of the form 9...989...9, called a palindromic wing prime or a near-repdigit palindromic prime.

A077795.name: Numbers k such that (10^k - 1)/9 + 8*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077796.name: Numbers k such that 7*(10^k - 1)/9 + 2*10^floor(k/2) is a palindromic wing prime (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic prime).

A077797.name: Numbers k for which there exist k-digit palindromic wing primes (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic primes) of the general form r*(10^k - 1)/9 + (m-r)*10^floor(k/2) where k is the number of digits (an odd number > 1), r is the repeated digit, and m (different from r) is the middle digit.

A077798.name: Palindromic wing primes (a.k.a. near-repdigit palindromic primes) of the general form r*(10^d - 1)/9 + (m-r)*10^floor(d/2) where d is the number of digits (an odd number > 1), r is the repeated digit, and m (different from r) is the middle digit.

A077799.name: Smoothly undulating palindromic primes of the general form (ab*10^m-ba)/99 exist for digit lengths a(n).

A077800.name: List of twin primes {p, p+2}.
formula: Sum_{n>=1} 1/a(n) is in the interval (1.840503, 2.288490) (Platt and Trudgian, 2020). The conjectured value based on assumptions about the distribution of twin primes is A065421. - _Amiram Eldar_, Oct 15 2020

A077801.name: Non-balanced numbers in A015767.
formula: Mod[sigma[9, a(n)], phi[a(n)]]=0; Mod[sigma[1, a(n)], phi[a(n)]]><0.

A077802.name: Sum of products of parts increased by 1 in hook partitions of n, where hook partitions are of the form h*1^(n-h).
formula: Row sums of triangle A132048. Equals binomial transform of [1, 1, 4, 2, 4, 2, 4, 2, 4,...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Aug 08 2007

A077803.name: Non-balanced numbers in A015769.
formula: Mod[sigma[11, a(n)], phi[a(n)]]=0; Mod[sigma[1, a(n)], phi[a(n)]]><0.

A077805.name: Smallest prime factor of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077806.name: Greatest prime factor of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077807.name: Number of distinct prime factors of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077808.name: Number of prime factors of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1 (counted with multiplicity).

A077809.name: Number of divisors of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077810.name: Sum of divisors of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077811.name: Euler's totient of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077812.name: Squarefree kernel of numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077813.name: Squarefree numbers containing in their decimal representation only the digits 0 and 1.

A077814.name: a(n) = #{0<=k<=n: mod(kn,4)=2}.
formula: a(n)=0 if n=4k, a(n)=k if n=4k+1, a(n)=2k+1 if n=4k+2 and a(n)=k+1 if n=4k+3.

A077815.name: 2^phi(n) mod n^2, where phi is Euler's totient function A000010.

A077816.name: Wieferich numbers (1): n > 1 such that 2^A000010(n) == 1 (mod n^2).

A077817.name: Number of self-avoiding walks on the cubic lattice trapped after n steps.

A077818.name: Probability P(n) of the occurrence of a 3-dimensional self-trapping walk of length n: numerator.

A077819.name: Probability P(n) of the occurrence of a 3-dimensional self-trapping walk of length n: exponent of 3 in the denominator.

A077820.name: Probability P(n) of the occurrence of a 3-dimensional self-trapping walk of length n: exponent of 2 in the denominator.

A077828.name: Expansion of 1/(1-3*x-3*x^2-3*x^3).
formula: a(n)=sum{k=0..n, T(n-k, k)3^(n-k)}, T(n, k) = trinomial coefficients (A027907). - _Paul Barry_, Feb 15 2005
a(n)=sum{k=0..n, sum{i=0..floor((n-k)/2), C(n-k-i, i)C(k, n-k-i)}*3^k}; - _Paul Barry_, Apr 26 2005

A077834.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 2*x - 2*x^2 - 3*x^3).
formula: a(n) = A152733(n+3)/3. - _Vladimir Joseph Stephan Orlovsky_, Dec 11 2008

A077835.name: Expansion of 1/(1-2*x-2*x^2-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = sum{k=0..n, T(n-k, k)2^(n-k)}, T(n, k) = trinomial coefficients (A027907). - _Paul Barry_, Feb 15 2005
a(n) = sum{k=0..n, sum{i=0..floor((n-k)/2), C(n-k-i, i)C(k, n-k-i)}*2^k} - _Paul Barry_, Apr 26 2005

A077839.name: Expansion of (1 - x)/(1 - 3*x - 2*x^2 - 2*x^3).
formula: Recurrence: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2) + 2*a(n-3) for n >= 3 with a(0) = 1, a(1) = 2, and a(3) = 8. [_Harvey P. Dale_, Apr 29 2011]

A077840.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-3*x^2-3*x^3).
formula: a(0)=1 and, for n >= 1, a(n) = Sum(k=1..n, Sum(i=k..n,(Sum(j=0..k, binomial(j,-3*k+2*j+i)*3^(-2*k+j+i)*binomial(k,j)))*binomial(n+k-i-1,k-1))). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 05 2011

A077841.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-3*x^2-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = sum(k=1..n, sum(i=k..n,(sum(j=0..k, binomial(j,-3*k+2*j+i)* 3^(-3*k+2*j+i)*2^(k-j)*binomial(k,j)))*binomial(n+k-i-1,k-1))), n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 05 2011

A077843.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-2*x^2-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = sum(k=1..n, sum(i=k..n,(sum(j=0..k, binomial(j,-3*k+2*j+i)*2^(-2*k+j+i)* binomial(k,j)))*binomial(n+k-i-1,k-1))). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 05 2011

A077846.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 3*x + 2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-3) = 2*A057960(n) - 1 = round(2*A028859(n)/sqrt(3) - 1/3) = Sum_i( b(n, i) ), where b(n, 0) = b(n, 6) = 0, b(0, 3) = 1, b(0, i) = 0 if i <> 3 and b(n+1, i) = b(n, i-1) + b(n, i) + b(n, i+1) if 0 < i < 6 (i.e., the number of three-choice paths along a corridor width 5, starting from the middle). - _Henry Bottomley_, Mar 06 2003
Binomial transform of A068911. a(n) = (1+sqrt(3))^n*(2+sqrt(3))/3 + (1-sqrt(3))^n*(2-sqrt(3))/3 - 1/3. - _Paul Barry_, Feb 17 2004
a(0)=1; for n >= 1, a(n) = ceiling((1+sqrt(3))*a(n-1)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 19 2004
a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n} 2^j*binomial(j, i-j))). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 23 2004

A077850.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1 - 2*x - x^2 + x^3).
formula: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3) + a(n-4), n>3. Also a(n)=Sum_{k=0..n} A188106(n,k), n=0,1,2,..., giving partial sums of first convolution of A006054 with itself. - _L. Edson Jeffery_, Apr 22 2011

A077854.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)*(1-2*x)*(1+x^2)).
formula: Row sums of A130306. - _Gary W. Adamson_, May 20 2007
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n+3} floor(1 + sin(k*Pi/2 + 3*Pi/4))*2^(n-k+3). - _Andres Cicuttin_, Mar 28 2016

A077855.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1 - 2*x + x^2 - x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..(n+3)} binomial((n+3)-i, (n+3)-3*i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jul 07 2020

A077859.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-2*x+2*x^2-x^3).
formula: a(n) = sum{k=0..n, binomial(n-2k, n-k-1)}; - _Paul Barry_, Jan 15 2005
a(n) = n + 1 + a(n-1) - a(n-2), with a(-1) = a(-2) = 0. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Jul 11 2013
a(n) = sum{k=0..n, (-1)^k*(n+1-k)*b(k)}, where b(n)=A049347(n). - _Mircea Merca_, Feb 04 2014

A077860.name: Expansion of 1/((1 - 2*x + 2*x^2)*(1-x)).
formula: G.f.: Q(0) where Q(k) = 1 + k*(2*x+1) + 8*x - 2*x*(k+1)*(k+5)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Mar 14 2013
G.f.: G(0)/(2*(1-x)^2), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+2) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013
a(n) = 1 + 2*Im((1 + i)^n), where i is the imaginary unit. - _Daniel Suteu_, Dec 21 2018

A077864.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-x-2*x^2-x^3).
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = Sum_{j=0..n/2} A027907(n+1-j,2*j+1), n >= 0. - _Werner Schulte_, Sep 29 2015

A077865.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-x-2*x^2+x^3).
formula: a(n)=a(n-1)+2a(n-2)-a(n-3)+1 for n>=3. a(n)=2a(n-1)+a(n-2)-3a(n-3)+a(n-4) for n>=4. - _Clark Kimberling_, Jun 26 2004

A077868.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-x-x^3).
formula: Partial sums of A000930. a(n-1) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-2k, k+1). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 07 2004

a(n-3) = Sum(binomial(n-r, r)), r=1, 2, ... which is the case t=3 and k=2 in the general case of t-strings and k blocks: a(n-3, k, t) = Sum(binomial(n-r*(t-1), r)*S2(n-r*(t-1)-1, k-1)), r=1, 2, ... - _Augustine O. Munagi_, Apr 11 2005
a(n) = -A077888(-4-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 17 2018

A077870.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-x+2*x^3).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(1 + x) where G(k) = 1 + 8*x + 2*k*x + k - 2*x*(k+1)*(k+5)/G(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 09 2013
G.f.: G(0)/(2*(1-x^2)*(1-x)), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+2) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013

A077872.name: Expansion of 1 / ((1-x)*(1-x+x^2+x^3)).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2) + a(n-4) for n>3. - _Colin Barker_, Jun 20 2017

A077876.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-x+2*x^2).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} U(k, 1/(2*sqrt(2))(2*sqrt(2))^k. - _Paul Barry_, Nov 20 2003 [There is a missing parenthesis, but it is not clear where it should be inserted. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Feb 08 2015)
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor((n+1)/2)} binomial(n+1-k,k+1)*(-2)^k,  n>=0. - _Taras Goy_, Apr 15 2020

A077879.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-2*x^2-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = sum(k=1..n, sum(j=floor((4*k-n)/3)..floor((4*k-n)/2), binomial(j,n-4*k+3*j)*(-1)^(k-j)*binomial(k,j)*2^(n-3*k+2*j))), n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 25 2011

A077880.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1-2*x^2+x^3).
formula: If 0 is prepended then BINOMIAL transform is A079282 with 0 prepended. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 31 2012

A077882.name: Expansion of x/((1-x)*(1-x^2-2*x^3)).
formula: a(n+1)=sum{k=0..n, sum{j=0..floor(k/2), C(j, k-2j)2^(k-2j)}}; - _Paul Barry_, Jul 18 2005

A077887.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1+x^2-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - a(n-2) + 3 a(n-3) - 2 a(n-4), with a(0) = a(1) = 1, a(2) = 0 and a(3) = 2. - _Jean-François Alcover_, Apr 06 2016
a(n) = n+1 - a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2), with a(0) = a(1) = 1. - _Michel Marcus_, Apr 06 2016

A077898.name: Expansion of (1 - x)^(-1)/(1 + x - 2*x^2).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..k} Sum_{i=0..j} binomial(j, i)*(-3)^i. - _Paul Barry_, Aug 26 2003

A077904.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1+x-2*x^3).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(2*(1-x^2)*(1-x)), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+2) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013

A077905.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - x^2 - x^3 + x^4).
formula: a(n) = sum(k=1..n/2, sum(j=0..k, binomial(j,n-4*k+2*j)*(-1)^(k-j)*binomial(k,j))), n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Oct 21 2011
a(-3-n) = -A023434(n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 25 2014

A077908.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1+x+x^2-x^3).
formula: a(n) = -a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) + 1 = 2*a(n-3) - a(n-4) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 19 2014
a(n) - a(n-1) = A057597(n+2). (first differences). - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 16 2017

A077909.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)*(1+x+x^2+2*x^3)).
formula: a(n) = (-1)^n*sum(A128099(n-2*k, n-3*k), k=0..floor(n/3)). - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Aug 28 2013

A077913.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)*(1+x+2*x^2+x^3)).
formula: G.f.: 1-x^2/(U(0)+x^2) where U(k)= 1 + (1+x)*x/( 1 - (1+x)*x/((1+x)*x + 1/U(k+1))) ; (continued fraction, 2-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 24 2012

A077914.name: Sums of two distinct primes in exactly two ways.

A077916.name: Expansion of (1-x)^(-1)/(1 + 2*x - 2*x^2 - x^3).
formula: O.g.f.: exp( Sum_{n >= 1} Lucas(n)^2*(-x)^n/n ) = 1 - x + 5*x^2 - 10*x^3 + .... Cf. A203803. See also A207969 and A207970. - _Peter Bala_, Apr 03 2014
a(n) = (F(2n+2)+n+1)/5 if n is odd and a(n)= -(F(2n+2)-n-1)/5 if n is even, where F(n) = Fibonacci numbers (A000045). - _Rigoberto Florez_, May 09 2019

A077925.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)*(1+2*x)).
formula: G.f.: Q(0)/(3*x), where Q(k) = 1 - 1/(4^k - 2*x*16^k/(2*x*4^k + 1/(1 + 1/(2*4^k - 8*x*16^k/(4*x*4^k - 1/Q(k+1)))))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 22 2013
G.f.: Q(0)/2 , where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(4*k-1 + 2*x)/( x*(4*k+1 + 2*x) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 08 2013

A077936.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 2*x - 2*x^2 - x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n-k} C(n-j,k)*C(2k,j). - _Paul Barry_, Mar 24 2009

A077938.name: Expansion of 1/(1-2*x-x^2-2*x^3).
formula: a(n)=sum(k=1..n, sum(j=0..k, binomial(j,n-3*k+2*j)* binomial(k,j)*2^(-n+4*k-2*j))), n>0, a(0)=1. [_Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 05 2011]

A077939.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - 2*x - x^2 - x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{m=1..n+1} Sum_(k=0..n-m+1} (Sum_{j=0..k} binomial(j,n-m-3*k+2*j+1) *binomial(k,j))*binomial(m+k-1,m-1). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Oct 11 2011
G.f. for sequence with 1 prepended: 1/(1 - Sum_{k>=0} x*(x+x^2+x^3)^k). - _Joerg Arndt_, Sep 30 2012
G.f.: Q(0)/2, where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1- x*(4*k+2 + x+x^2)/(x*(4*k+4 + x+x^2) + 1/Q(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 04 2013
a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2) + a(n-3), where a(0) = 0, a(1)=1, a(2)=2. - _Rigoberto Florez_, Jan 23 2020

A077942.name: Expansion of 1/(1-2*x+x^2+2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..(n+1)/2} binomial(n+1-k,2k+1)*(-2)^k, n>=0. - _Taras Goy_, Apr 15 2020

A077946.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - x - 2*x^2 - 2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = leftmost term in M^n * [1 0 0], where M = the 3X3 matrix [1 1 1 / 2 0 0 / 0 1 0]. a(n) = a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2) + 2*a(n-3). a(n)/a(n-1) tends to 2.26953084..., an eigenvalue of M and a root of the characteristic polynomial x^3 - x^2 - 2x - 2. a(6) = 79 = 35 + 2*15 + 2*7 = a(5) + 2*a(4) + 2*a(3). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 21 2004

A077947.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - x - x^2 - 2*x^3).
formula: Convolution of A000079 and A049347. a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} 2^k*2*sqrt(3)*cos(2*Pi(n-k)/3+Pi/6)/3. - _Paul Barry_, May 19 2004
Partial sums of A078010 starting (1, 0, 1, 3, 4, 9, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, May 13 2013

A077948.name: Expansion of 1/(1-x-x^2+2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3). If defined by this recurrence, the sequence could be preceded by 0, 0. - _Paul Curtz_, Feb 17 2008

A077949.name: Expansion of 1/(1-x-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} C(n-2k, k)*2^k. - _Paul Barry_, Nov 18 2003
a(n) = term (1,1) in the 3x3 matrix [1,1,0; 0,0,1; 2,0,0]^n. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Aug 16 2008
G.f.: Q(0)/2, where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k+1 + 2*x^2)/( x*(2*k+2 + 2*x^2) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 29 2013

A077950.name: Expansion of 1/(1-x+2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - 2*a(n-3), where a(0)=1, a(1)=1, a(2)=1. - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 21 2012
G.f.: G(0)/(2*(1-x^2)), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+2) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..floor((n+2)/2)} binomial(n+2-2*k, k-1)*(-2)^(k-1). - _Taras Goy_, Sep 18 2019

A077952.name: Expansion of 1/(1 - x + x^2 + 2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n} C(k,j-k)*C(k,n-j)*(-2)^(n-j). - _Paul Barry_, Mar 09 2006

A077954.name: Expansion of 1/(1-x+2*x^2-x^3) in powers of x.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2) + a(n-3) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 13 2013

A077957.name: Powers of 2 alternating with zeros.
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-2) with a(0)=1, a(1)=0. - _Jim Singh_, Jul 12 2018

A077958.name: Expansion of 1/(1-2*x^3).
formula: G.f.: A(x) = x/(x-1)*G(0); G(k) = 1 - 1/(x - 2*x^5/(2*x^4 - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction, 3-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 25 2012
a(n) = 2^(n/3) if 3 divides n, otherwise a(n) = 0 (see Exercise 2 in Grinberg).

A077960.name: Trajectory of 18 under iteration of the map k -> A087712(k).

A077961.name: Expansion of 1 / (1 + x^2 - x^3) in powers of x.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(k, n-2k)(-1)^(n-k). - _Paul Barry_, Jun 24 2005
G.f.: Q(0)/2 , where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x^2*(4*k+1 - x )/( x^2*(4*k+3 - x ) - 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 09 2013

A077969.name: Numbers which can be expressed as the sum of two distinct primes in exactly three ways.

A077972.name: Expansion of 1/(1+x-x^2+2*x^3).
formula: G.f.: Q(0)/2 , where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(4*k+1 - x + 2*x^2 )/( x*(4*k+3 - x + 2*x^2 ) - 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 09 2013

A077973.name: Expansion of 1/(1+x-2*x^3).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(2*(1-x^2)), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+2) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013

A077975.name: Expansion of 1/(1+x+x^2-2*x^3).
formula: Recurrence: a(n) = 2a(n-3) - a(n-2) - a(n-1), starting 1,-1,0. - _Ralf Stephan_, Aug 18 2013

A077979.name: Expansion of 1/(1+x+2*x^2+x^3).
formula: G.f.: 1 - x/(G(0) + x) where G(k)= 1 - x*(k+1)/(1 - 1/(1 + (k+1)/G(k+1)));(continued fraction, 3-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 17 2012

A077982.name: Min(P in Partitions(n), Sum(k in P, d(k))) where d(k) = number of divisors of k (A000005).
formula: If n is prime then a(n) = 2 else if n + 1 is prime or n = p^2 for p prime then a(n) = 3. - _David A. Corneth_, Dec 27 2017

A077984.name: Expansion of 1/(1+2*x-2*x^2+2*x^3).
formula: a(n) is the nearest integer to c*d^n where c=0.7166689603... satisfies 67*c^3 - 67*c^2 + 15*c - 1 = 0 and d=-2.9196395658... satisfies d^3 + 2*d^2 - 2*d + 2 = 0.

A077985.name: Expansion of 1/(1 + 2*x - x^2).
formula: a(0)=1, a(1)=-2, a(n) = -2*a(n-1) + a(n-2) for n>1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 19 2009
G.f.: 1/(2+Q(0)), where Q(k)= 3*x - 1 + x*k + x*(1-x)*(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 05 2013
G.f.: Q(0)/(2+2*x), where Q(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k-1)/( x*(2*k+1) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 10 2013
G.f.: Q(0)/2, where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(4*k+2 - x )/( x*(4*k+4 - x) - 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 09 2013
a(n) = (-1)^n * a(-2-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 20 2017

A077995.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-2*x^2-x^3).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{m=1..n} Sum_{i=0..n-m} C(m+i-1,m-1)*Sum_{j=0..m} C(j,n-3*m +2*j-i) * C(m,j)*2^(n-3*m+2*j-i), n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 12 2011
G.f.: 1 + x/(G(0)-x) where G(k)=  1 - x*(2*k+2)/(1 - 1/(1 + (2*k+2)/G(k+1)));(continued fraction, 3-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 17 2012

A077996.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-x^2-2*x^3).
formula: If p[1]=1, p[2]=2, p[i]=4, (i>2), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 02 2010
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} Sum_{i=k..n} Sum_{j=0..k} binomial(j,-3*k+2*j+i) * 2^(k-j)*binomial(k,j)*binomial(n+k-i-1,k-1). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 05 2011

A077997.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-x^2-x^3).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2) + a(n-3), n>2, with a(0)=1, a(1)=1, a(2)=3. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 20 2008

If p[1]=1, p[2]=2, p[i]=3, (i>2), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 02 2010
a(n) = Sum_{m=1..n} Sum_{i=0..n-m} binomial(m+i-1,m-1)*Sum_{j=0..m} binomial(j,n-3*m+2*j-i)*binomial(m,j), n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 12 2011

A077998.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-x^2+x^3).
formula: a(0)=a(1)=1, a(2)=3, a(n+1) = 2*a(n) + a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n>=2. - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 07 2006

7*a(n) = (s(2))^2*(1+c(1))^n + (s(4))^2*(1+c(2))^n + (s(1))^2(1+c(4))^n, where c(j) = 2*Cos(2Pi*j/7) and s(j) = 2*Sin(2Pi*j/7) - for the proof of this one and many other relations for the sequences u(k), v(k) and w(k) defined on the top of the comments by _Benoit Cloitre_ - see Witula et al.'s paper. - _Roman Witula_, Aug 07 2012
a(n) = b(n+2)- b(n+1), first differences of b(n) = A006054(n). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Nov 07 2013; corrected by _Kai Wang_, May 31 2017

A077999.name: Expansion of (1-x)/(1-2*x-2*x^3).
formula: a(n) = 2*(a(n-1) + a(n-3)) counts the above permutations by first entry. a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) + 3*Sum_{k=0..n-3} a(k) counts by last entry. a(n) = 2^(n-1) + Sum_{k=0..n-3} 2^(n-2-k)*a(k) counts by location of first 3xx pattern. a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/3)} ((n-k)/(n-2k))* binomial(n-2*k,k) * 2^(n-2*k-1) counts by number of 3xx patterns. - _David Callan_, Oct 26 2006
